  "prompt": "What are substitutes for parsnips in recipes?",
  "response": "When parsnips aren't available or you simply want to try something different, there are several substitutes that can work well in recipes. Here are some options:\n\n### **Root Vegetables (for roasting, mashing, or soups)**\n1. **Carrots** - Sweet and tender, they\u2019re a great substitute in most recipes.\n2. **Turnips** - Mildly sweet with a slightly peppery flavor, they work well in stews or roasts.\n3. **Celery Root (Celeriac)** - Earthy and nutty, perfect for mashing or soups.\n4. **Parsley Root** - Closest in flavor to parsnips, though it can be harder to find.\n5. **Sweet Potatoes** - Adds sweetness and creaminess, ideal for mashing or roasting.\n6. **Rutabaga** - Slightly sweet and peppery, good in soups and stews.\n7. **Potatoes** - Starchy and neutral, great for mashing or roasting.\n\n### **Vegetables for Specific Uses**\n- **Cauliflower** - Works well in purees or roasted dishes.\n- **Butternut Squash** - Sweet and creamy, ideal for soups or purees.\n- **Daikon Radish** - Mild and slightly peppery, good in stews or stir-fries.\n\n### **Other Substitutes**\n- **Plantains** - Sweet and starchy, great in Caribbean-inspired dishes.\n- **Jicama** - Crunchy and mildly sweet, good in salads or slaws.\n\n### **Tips for Substituting**\n- Adjust cooking times as different vegetables may cook faster or slower than parsnips.\n- Consider the flavor profile of the dish when choosing a substitute (e.g., sweetness, earthiness, or starchiness).\n\nLet me know if you need help with a specific recipe!",
